                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d530">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European War 1939/44: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-07T15:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 7, 1939—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 7—11:02 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2377. Leger<note n="81" xml:id="d530fn81">Secretary General of the French Foreign
                        Office.</note> informed me this morning that the French Government has
                    decided that Hitler’s speech requires no reply and that any observations on it
                    may be made fittingly in the course of routine utterances by members of the
                    French and British Governments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
